        },
        {
          "@type": "ListItem",
          "position": 4,
          "name": "Scroll Wheel Test",
          "item": "https://toolkify.com/tools/display/scroll-wheel"
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <!-- FAQ JSON-LD Schema -->
  <script type="application/ld+json" is:inline>
    {
      "@context": "https://schema.org",
      "@type": "FAQPage",
      "mainEntity": [
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to test mouse scroll wheel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>To test your mouse scroll wheel online, visit the Scroll Wheel Test tool on TOOLKIFY. Move your mouse pointer into the dashed test zone and rotate your scroll wheel up or down. The tool instantly captures every tick, measures scroll speed in pixels per second, and shows a live delta waveform. If your scroll wheel is working normally you will see consistent tick counts and a steady velocity reading. If the counter skips, jumps, or registers ticks in the wrong direction, your scroll wheel encoder may need cleaning or replacement.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to fix mouse scroll wheel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>The most common fixes for a faulty mouse scroll wheel are: (1) <strong>Clean the encoder</strong> â€” use compressed air or a cotton swab with isopropyl alcohol around the scroll wheel to remove dust and debris that cause erratic ticks. (2) <strong>Update mouse drivers</strong> â€” outdated or corrupt drivers can make the scroll wheel behave irregularly; reinstall from the manufacturer's website. (3) <strong>Adjust Windows/macOS scroll settings</strong> â€” go to your system's mouse settings and recalibrate the scroll speed. (4) <strong>Replace the rotary encoder</strong> â€” if cleaning does not help, the physical encoder inside the mouse may be worn out and can be replaced with a compatible part. Use a scroll wheel test tool first to confirm the exact fault before opening the mouse.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "Why is my scroll wheel not working?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>There are several reasons your scroll wheel may not be working: a dirty or worn rotary encoder inside the mouse, outdated or corrupted device drivers, incorrect OS scroll speed settings set to zero, a USB port or wireless receiver connectivity issue, or a software conflict. To diagnose the problem, run a scroll wheel test online â€” if the tool captures zero events, the issue is hardware or driver related. If the test captures events but they are erratic or reversed, the encoder is likely dirty or failing.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to disable scroll wheel?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>You can disable a mouse scroll wheel in several ways depending on your operating system. On <strong>Windows</strong>, open the Registry Editor (regedit), navigate to HKEY_CURRENT_USER\\Control Panel\\Desktop, and set the WheelScrollLines value to 0. Alternatively, use third-party tools such as WheelBlocker or PowerToys to selectively disable scroll wheel input for specific apps. On <strong>macOS</strong>, you can use USB Overdrive or Scroll Reverser to disable or remap the scroll wheel. For gaming or accessibility needs, AutoHotkey scripts on Windows can intercept and suppress wheel events at the application level.</p>"
          }
        },
        {
          "@type": "Question",
          "name": "How to fix mouse scroll wheel going up and down?",
          "acceptedAnswer": {
            "@type": "Answer",
            "text": "<p>A mouse scroll wheel that randomly jumps up and down while you are only scrolling in one direction is usually caused by a failing or dirty rotary encoder. The encoder's contact brushes become worn and generate erratic electrical signals that the mouse firmware interprets as direction reversals. To fix this: (1) Open the mouse and clean the scroll wheel encoder with isopropyl alcohol to remove carbon deposits. (2) If the problem persists after cleaning, replace the encoder â€” a 30-pulse encoder (EC11 type) is common and inexpensive. (3) On the software side, some mice drivers have a scroll correction setting that can suppress minor reversals. Use a free scroll wheel test tool to verify whether the jumping is fully resolved after each step.</p>"
          }
        }
      ]
    }
  </script>

  <section
